The defendant Rebecca A Gomez was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Bail Jumping-Felony, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(b).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Notice of Failure to Meet Condition for Expungement.
**Reviewed by Judge Michael J. Aprahamian on 8/29/17.**
Wis. Dept. of Corrections notice of case status change received.  Outstanding financial obligations have been satisfied.
Amended one - COSTS PAID FROM BAIL

Defendant Rebecca A Gomez in court with attorney Eryn M Menden.  Brian J. Juech appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant enters a guilty plea to Count 1.  Court finds defendant guilty.

Court orders the following: 
Ct. 1:
-  Withheld sentence for 2 years Probation - concurrent to 14CF917 - 10 days credit if revoked
- Court Costs of $268.00 to be paid as a Condition of Probation 
- DNA Surcharge of $250.00 to be paid as a Condition of Probation - apply bail
- Conditions of  Probation: Maintain absolute sobriety. Random U.A.'s..   Follow thru with any treatment/counseling recommended by Agent.  Any valid prescription drugs must be taken only in the manner in which they are prescribed; Inform Agent of all prescriptions. Maintain full-time employment and/or combination of schooling. No contact with witnesses with the exception of her parents.  Defendant to provide DNA sample, if not yet provided, immediately if in custody otherwise within (3) business days at the Waukesha County Sheriff Department. 
 -  20 days jail Condition Time (nonworking hours) STAYED to be used at the Agents discretion. Huber/Straight time to be used at the discretion of Agent. 

Court will permit early termination of probation after 18 months if defendant successfully completes probation and the agent approves the early termination. 

Court finds that society would not be harmed and if the defendant has no new law violations while on probation Court will grant expungement.
